{"title_page": "Pyon In-son", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|birth_date  = 1946\n|death_date  = \n|occupation=Military officer, politician\n|birth_place=\n|education   = \n|party       = [[Workers' Party of Korea]]\n|nationality = [[Korean people|Korean]]\n|citizenship = [[Citizenship in North Korea|North Korean]]\n|allegiance  = {{flag|North Korea|1948}}\n|branch      = {{armed forces|North Korea}}\n|alma_mater  = \n|serviceyears = \n|rank        = [[image:Major General rank insignia (North Korea).svg|25px]] [[Major general#North Korea|Major general]]\n|battles     = \n}}\n'''Pyon In-son ({{lang-ko|\ubcc0\uc778 \uc120}})''' (born 1946) is North Korean politician and military office, colonel general and from March 2012 commander of the [[IV Corps (North Korea)|4th Corps]] of the [[Korean People's Army]].\n\n==Biography==\nHe received his general qualifications and the rank of major-general (cor. \uc18c\uc7a5) in 1992. He was promoted to the rank of two-star lieutenant-general (kor. \uc911\uc7a5) on April 13, 1997. In July 2003 he was promoted to the rank of colonel general (kor coronation). Former commander of the [[VII Corps (North Korea)|7th Corps]] of the Korean People's Army, in August 2011 appointed commander of the 4th Corps of the Korean People's Army, which is stationed in [[South Hwanghae Province]]. He replaced General [[Kim Kyok-sik]] in this position<ref>\uc774\uc6a9\uc218, [http://news.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2012/03/07/2012030700150.html ''\uc5f0\ud3c9\ub3c4 \ub3c4\ubc1c \u5317 4\uad70\ub2e8\uc7a5, \uae40\uaca9\uc2dd \ud6c4\uc784\uc5d0 \ubcc0\uc778\uc120''] {{lang|ko}}, \uc870\uc120\uc77c\ubcf4 (Chosun.com), 7 marca 2012].</ref>.\n\nDuring the 3rd Korean Workers' Party of Korea Conference on September 28, 2010, he was elected a member of the [[Central Committee of the Workers' Party of Korea|Central Committee]] of the [[Workers' Party of Korea]]. Member of the [[2003 North Korea parliamentary election|eleventh]] and [[2009 North Korean parliamentary election|twelfth]] convocations of the [[Supreme People's Assembly]], the North Korea's [[unicameralism|unicameral parliament]]. After the [[death]] of [[Kim Jong-il]] in December 2011, Pyon In-son was ranked 63rd in the [[Death and funeral of Kim Jong-il|233-person Funeral Committee]]<ref>[http://archive.is/wu4bS ''Kim Jong Il Funeral Committee (as of 19 December 2011)''], NK Leadership Watch, 21 grudnia 2011, [dost\u0119p: 26 lipca 2012]</ref>. According to specialists, places on such lists defined the rank of politician in the hierarchy of the power apparatus<ref>[http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2011/12/20/2011122001740.html ''Clues from Kim Jong-il Funeral List''], The Chosun Ilbo, 20 grudnia 2011, [dost\u0119p: 26 lipca 2012].</ref><ref>Tetsuya Hakoda, [http://web.archive.org/web/20160303234008/http://ajw.asahi.com/article/asia/korean_peninsula/AJ201112270036 ''All eyes set on Kim Jong Il's funeral committee list''], The Asahi Shimbun, 27 grudnia 2011, [dost\u0119p: 26 lipca 2012].</ref>.\n\nIn February 2012, he accompanied [[Kim Jong-un]] during the inspection of the 4th Corps barracks.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:North Korean generals]]\n[[Category:Members of the Supreme People's Assembly]]\n[[Category:Workers' Party of Korea politicians]]\n\n[[pl:Py\u014fn In S\u014fn]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|birth_date  = 1946\n|death_date  = \n|occupation=Military officer, politician\n|birth_place=\n|education   = \n|party       = [[Workers' Party of Korea]]\n|nationality = [[Korean people|Korean]]\n|citizenship = [[Citizenship in North Korea|North Korean]]\n|allegiance  = {{flag|North Korea|1948}}\n|branch      = {{armed forces|North Korea}}\n|alma_mater  = \n|serviceyears = \n|rank        = [[image:Major General rank insignia (North Korea).svg|25px]] [[Major general#North Korea|Major general]]\n|battles     = \n}}\n'''Pyon In-son ({{lang-ko|\ubcc0\uc778 \uc120}})''' (born 1946) is North Korean politician and military office, colonel general and from March 2012 commander of the [[IV Corps (North Korea)|4th Corps]] of the [[Korean People's Army]].\n\n==Biography==\nHe received his general qualifications and the rank of major-general (cor. \uc18c\uc7a5) in 1992. He was promoted to the rank of two-star lieutenant-general (kor. \uc911\uc7a5) on April 13, 1997. In July 2003 he was promoted to the rank of colonel general (kor coronation). Former commander of the [[VII Corps (North Korea)|7th Corps]] of the Korean People's Army, in August 2011 appointed commander of the 4th Corps of the Korean People's Army, which is stationed in [[South Hwanghae Province]]. He replaced General [[Kim Kyok-sik]] in this position<ref>\uc774\uc6a9\uc218, [http://news.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2012/03/07/2012030700150.html ''\uc5f0\ud3c9\ub3c4 \ub3c4\ubc1c \u5317 4\uad70\ub2e8\uc7a5, \uae40\uaca9\uc2dd \ud6c4\uc784\uc5d0 \ubcc0\uc778\uc120''] {{lang|ko}}, \uc870\uc120\uc77c\ubcf4 (Chosun.com), 7 marca 2012].</ref>.\n\nDuring the 3rd Korean Workers' Party of Korea Conference on September 28, 2010, he was elected a member of the [[Central Committee of the Workers' Party of Korea|Central Committee]] of the [[Workers' Party of Korea]]. Member of the [[2003 North Korea parliamentary election|eleventh]] and [[2009 North Korean parliamentary election|twelfth]] convocations of the [[Supreme People's Assembly]], the North Korea's [[unicameralism|unicameral parliament]]. After the [[death]] of [[Kim Jong-il]] in December 2011, Pyon In-son was ranked 63rd in the [[Death and funeral of Kim Jong-il|233-person Funeral Committee]]<ref>[http://archive.is/wu4bS ''Kim Jong Il Funeral Committee (as of 19 December 2011)''] {{lang|en}}, NK Leadership Watch, 21 grudnia 2011, [dost\u0119p: 26 lipca 2012]</ref>. According to specialists, places on such lists defined the rank of politician in the hierarchy of the power apparatus<ref>[http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2011/12/20/2011122001740.html ''Clues from Kim Jong-il Funeral List''] {{lang|en}}, The Chosun Ilbo, 20 grudnia 2011, [dost\u0119p: 26 lipca 2012].</ref><ref>Tetsuya Hakoda, [http://web.archive.org/web/20160303234008/http://ajw.asahi.com/article/asia/korean_peninsula/AJ201112270036 ''All eyes set on Kim Jong Il's funeral committee list''] {{lang|en}}, The Asahi Shimbun, 27 grudnia 2011, [dost\u0119p: 26 lipca 2012].</ref>.\n\nIn February 2012, he accompanied [[Kim Jong-un]] during the inspection of the 4th Corps barracks.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:North Korean generals]]\n[[Category:Members of the Supreme People's Assembly]]\n[[Category:Workers' Party of Korea politicians]]\n", "name_user": "Rakoon", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pyon_In-son"}
{"title_page": "Ruth Westheimer", "text_new": "{{short description|German-American sex therapist}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name          = Ruth Westheimer\n|image         = Ruth Westheimer (10877).jpg\n|caption       = Westheimer in 2018\n|birth_name    = Karola Ruth Siegel\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1928|6|4}}\n|birth_place   = [[Karlstadt am Main|Wiesenfeld]], [[Weimar Republic|Germany]]\n|death_date    = \n|death_place   = \n|other_names   = Dr. Ruth\n|education     = [[University of Paris]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br />[[The New School|New School]] ([[Master of Arts|MA]])<br />[[Columbia University]] ([[Doctor of Education|EdD]])\n|spouse        = Fred Westheimer (1961\u20131997)\n|children      = 2, including [[Joel Westheimer|Joel]]\n|signature_alt = Signature of Dr. Ruth\n|website       = {{Official URL}}\n| module             = {{Infobox military person|embed=yes\n   | allegiance      = {{flag|United States}}<br> {{flag|Germany}} <br> {{flag|Israel}}\n   | branch          = [[File:Haganah Symbol.svg|20px]] [[Haganah]]\n   | battles          = [[1947\u20131949 Israel War of Independence]]\n   | serviceyears    = 1946\u20131949\n}}\n}}\n'''Ruth Westheimer''' (born June 4, 1928), better known as '''Dr. Ruth''', is a [[German Americans|German American]] [[sex therapist]], media personality, author, radio, television talk show host, and [[Holocaust survivor]]. Her media career began in 1980 with the radio show ''Sexually Speaking'', which continued until 1990. She has hosted several series on the [[Lifetime (TV network)|Lifetime]] Channel and other [[cable television]] networks from 1984 to 1993 and is the author of 45 books on sex and sexuality.\n\n== Early life and education ==\nWestheimer was born '''Karola Ruth Siegel''' on June 4, 1928, in Wiesenfeld (now part of [[Karlstadt am Main]]), [[Weimar Republic|Germany]], the only child of [[Orthodox Judaism|Orthodox Jews]], Irma (n\u00e9e Hanauer), a housekeeper, and Julius Siegel, a [[Notions (sewing)|notions]] wholesaler and son of the family for whom Irma worked.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://jwa.org/encyclopedia/article/westheimer-ruth|title=Ruth Westheimer|publisher=JWA.org|date=March 1, 2009 |accessdate=December 18, 2016}}</ref> She was given an early grounding in [[Judaism]] by her father, who took her regularly to the synagogue in the [[Nordend (Frankfurt am Main)|Nordend]] district of [[Frankfurt]], where they lived. Her father was taken away by the Nazis a week after [[Kristallnacht]], or the Night of Broken Glass, in 1938. Westheimer cried while her father was taken away by men in gloss-finished boots, while her grandmother gave the men money and asked them to care for him. Westheimer's mother and grandmother decided that Germany was too dangerous due to the tension and Nazi violence growing, so in January 1939 they sent Westheimer on a \"[[Kindertransport|Kinder Transport]],\" a transport taking Jewish children going to Switzerland. 11-year-old Westheimer arrived at an orphanage of a Jewish charity in [[Heiden, Switzerland]], and took on the role of a caregiver and mother-like figure to the younger children there. Westheimer was not allowed to take classes at the local school, but a fellow orphan boy would sneak his textbooks to Westheimer at night so she could learn and continue her education.\n\nWhile at the orphanage, Westheimer corresponded with her mother and grandmother via letters. When the letters ceased in 1941, Westheimer knew she would not hear from them again. The details of her parents' deaths due to the Holocaust are also included in the Hulu documentary about Westheimer titled \"Ask Dr. Ruth\". Her father was killed in the [[Auschwitz concentration camp|Auschwitz]] concentration camp in 1942. Her mother was killed during the Holocaust, but there is no specific information about her death, or about how and when she died. In the data base at the [[Yad Vashem]] World Holocaust Remembrance Center, Westheimer's mother is categorized by the word ''verschollen'' or 'disappeared.'\n\nWestheimer decided to emigrate to British-controlled [[Mandatory Palestine]]. There, at 17, she \"first had sexual intercourse on a starry night, in a haystack, without contraception.\" She later told ''[[The New York Times]]'' that \"I am not happy about that, but I know much better now and so does everyone who listens to my radio program.\"<ref name=\"NYT\">Dullea, Georgia. \"[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9B0DE5D9103FF935A15753C1A961948260 Therapist to Therapist: Analyzing Dr. Ruth]\". ''[[The New York Times]]''. October 26, 1987.</ref> Westheimer joined the [[Haganah]] in [[Jerusalem]]. Because of her diminutive height of {{height|ft=4|in=7|abbr=MOS}},<ref name=\"NYT\" /> she was trained as a [[Reconnaissance|scout]] and [[sniper]].<ref name=\"snopes-sniper\">[http://www.snopes.com/medical/doctor/drruth.asp Urban Legends Reference Pages: Dr. Ruth Was a Sniper] by Barbara Mikkelson, March 1, 2007, Retrieved March 2, 2007.</ref> Of this experience, she said, \"I never killed anybody, but I know how to throw hand grenades and shoot.\"<ref name=\"2013_usatoday\">{{cite news|last1=Jayson|first1=Sharon|title=Dr. Ruth, pushing age 85, still talking about sex.|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2013/05/15/dr-ruth-westheimer-sex/2162073/|accessdate=March 25, 2017|newspaper=USA Today|date=May 15, 2013}}</ref> In 1948, Westheimer was seriously wounded in action by an exploding [[Shell (projectile)|shell]] during the [[1947\u20131949 Palestine war]], and it was several months before she was able to walk again.<ref name=\"GAH\">{{cite web|url=http://www.germanheritage.com/biographies/mtoz/westheimer.html|title=German-American Corner: Ruth Westheimer|website=www.germanheritage.com|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"NatGeo\">Foreman, Tom (June 11, 2003). [http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2003/06/0611_030611_drruth_2.html Dr. Ruth: Sex Sage and Ex-Sniper on Global Sexuality]. ''National Geographic''.</ref>\n\nIn 1950, Westheimer moved to France, where she studied and then taught psychology at the [[University of Paris]]. In 1956, she [[Immigration to the United States|immigrated to the United States]], settling in [[Washington Heights, Manhattan]].<ref name=\"Morris\">\"Morris, Bob. \"[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9802E5D71439F932A15751C1A963958260 At Home With: Dr. Ruth Westheimer; The Bible as Sex Manual?]\". ''[[The New York Times]]''. December 21, 1995.</ref><ref name=\"OpenMind\">\"[https://archive.org/details/openmind_ep1496 America's Significant Other: Dr. Ruth (1991)]\" ''OpenMind'' 1991.</ref> Westheimer earned an [[Master of Arts|M.A.]] degree in [[sociology]] from [[The New School]] in 1959<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.drruth.com/content/view/42/27/|title=All About Dr. Ruth|author=Administrator|work=drruth.com}}</ref> and an [[Doctor of Education|Ed.D.]] degree from [[Teachers College, Columbia University]] in 1970.<ref name=\"education\">{{cite news| first =Joanne| last =Kaufman| title =Dr. Ruth Westheimer: Her Bedrooms Are Off Limits| quote =\"I wanted it badly because of the view,\" said the radio and television sex therapist and author who's known simply as Dr. Ruth (the honorific comes courtesy of her Ph.D. in education).| newspaper =[[The New York Times]]| date =November 29, 2013| url =https://www.nytimes.com/2013/12/01/realestate/dr-ruth-westheimer-her-bedrooms-are-off-limits.html| accessdate =July 30, 2015}}</ref>\n\nWestheimer became a [[Citizenship of the United States|naturalized U.S. citizen]] in 1965.<ref name=\"US\">{{cite news|last1=Katz|first1=Mallory M.|title=10 Women Immigrants Who Changed Art, Thought, and Politics in the U.S.|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/10-women-immigrants-who-changed-art-thought-and-politics_us_58d08b72e4b0e0d348b3473f|accessdate=March 25, 2017|work=Huffington Post|date=March 20, 2017}}</ref> She regained her [[German nationality law|German citizenship]] in 2007 through the [[German Citizenship Project]] that enabled descendants of Germans deprived of their citizenship during the [[Third Reich]] to reclaim their citizenship without losing the citizenship of their home country.<ref name=\"German_citizen\">{{cite news|url=http://worldnews.nbcnews.com/_news/2012/04/16/11230508-descendants-of-holocaust-victims-reclaim-german-citizenship?lite|title=Descendants of Holocaust Victims Reclaim German Citizenship|last=Snyder|first=Don|date=April 16, 2012|accessdate=June 12, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161024193154/http://worldnews.nbcnews.com/_news/2012/04/16/11230508-descendants-of-holocaust-victims-reclaim-german-citizenship|archive-date=October 24, 2016|url-status=dead|publisher=NBC News}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://forward.com/news/154277/jews-stream-back-to-germany/|title=Jews Stream Back to Germany|last=Snyder|first=Donald|date=April 8, 2012|website=[[The Forward]]|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171225174644/https://forward.com/news/154277/jews-stream-back-to-germany/|archive-date=December 25, 2017|url-status=live|access-date=June 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Early career ==\n\nAfter receiving her Ed.D., she briefly worked for [[Planned Parenthood]] and this experience encouraged her to continue studying [[human sexuality]]. She went on to work as a [[postdoctoral researcher]] for [[Helen Singer Kaplan]] at [[New York-Presbyterian Hospital]].<ref name=GAH /> She continued to work there as an adjunct associate professor for five years. She also taught at [[Lehman College]], [[Brooklyn College]], [[Adelphi University]], [[Columbia University]] and [[United States Military Academy|West Point]].<ref name=\"dr_ruth_dot_com\">{{cite web|title=All About Dr. Ruth.|url=http://www.drruth.com/content/view/42/27|website=DrRuth.com|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Media career ==\nDr. Ruth's media career began in 1980 when her radio show, ''Sexually Speaking'', debuted on [[WQHT#WYNY|WYNY-FM]] in New York City.<ref name=\"Sterling\">{{cite book|last1=Sterling|first1=Christopher H.|title=Biographical Encyclopedia of American Radio|date=2011|publisher=Routledge|location=New York City|isbn=978-0-415-99549-8|page=423|url=https://books.google.com/?id=mdQq-663faAC&pg=PA423&lpg=PA423&dq=dr.+ruth+WYNY+1980#v=onepage&q=dr.%20ruth%20WYNY%201980&f=false|accessdate=March 25, 2017}}</ref> She was offered this opportunity after she gave a lecture to New York broadcasters about the need for [[sex education]] programming to help deal with issues of [[contraception]] and unwanted pregnancies. Betty Elam, the community affairs manager at WYNY, was impressed with her talk and offered Westheimer [[United States dollar|$]]25 per week to make ''Sexually Speaking'', which started as a 15-minute show airing every Sunday at midnight.<ref name=\"biography\">{{cite web|last1=Staff Writers|title=Dr. Ruth Westheimer Biography.|url=http://www.biography.com/people/dr-ruth-westheimer-9542073|website=Biography.com|accessdate=March 25, 2017}}</ref> By 1983 her show was the top-rated radio show in the area, and in 1984 [[NBC Radio]] began [[Broadcast syndication|syndicating]] it nationwide as the ''Dr. Ruth Show''. She went on to produce her radio show until 1990.<ref name=\"Makers\">{{cite web|title=Interview with Dr. Ruth Westheimer.|url=http://www.makers.com/dr-ruth-westheimer|website=www.makers.com|accessdate=March 25, 2017}}</ref> Described as the \"[[Sister Wendy]] of Sexuality\", Dr. Ruth helped to revolutionize talk about sex and sexuality on radio and television, and she was noted for having \"an accent only a psychologist could love\".<ref name=\"Barron\">{{cite news|last1=Barron|first1=James|title=ART/ARCHITECTURE; Some Things Never Age. Just Ask Dr. Ruth.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/12/13/arts/art-architecture-some-things-never-age-just-ask-dr-ruth.html?pagewanted=2&src=pm|accessdate=March 25, 2017|newspaper=New York Times|date=December 13, 1998}}</ref> She became known for being candid and funny, but respectful, and for her tag phrase \"Get some\".<ref name=\"Kahn\">{{cite news|last1=Kahn|first1=Joseph P.|title=A sex expert for the ages.|url=http://archive.boston.com/lifestyle/articles/2011/04/07/dr_ruth_westheimer_discusses_her_career_as_a_sex_therapist/|accessdate=March 25, 2017|newspaper=Boston Globe|date=April 7, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Griset\">{{cite news|last1=Griset|first1=Rich|title=Moment of Ruth.|url=http://www.styleweekly.com/richmond/moment-of-ruth/Content?oid=2121380|accessdate=March 25, 2017|publisher=Style Weekly|date=September 23, 2014}}</ref> One journalist described her unique voice as \"a cross between [[Henry Kissinger]] and [[Minnie Mouse]]\".<ref name=\"Schuessler\">{{cite news|last1=Schuessler|first1=Jennifer|title=Audiences Can Now Analyze Dr. Ruth.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/06/24/theater/new-play-about-dr-ruth-westheimer.html|accessdate=March 25, 2017|newspaper=New York Times|date=June 21, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 1984, Westheimer began hosting several television programs on the [[Lifetime (TV network)|Lifetime]] TV network and one in syndication. Her first show was ''Good Sex! With Dr. Ruth Westheimer'', airing for a half hour at 10&nbsp;pm on weeknights. This show was expanded in 1985 to a full hour and its name was changed to ''The Dr. Ruth Show''. In 1987 she began a separate half hour syndicated series on many broadcast stations called ''Ask Dr. Ruth'' which was co-hosted by Larry Angelo. Dr. Ruth returned to the Lifetime network in 1988 with ''The All New Dr. Ruth Show'', which was followed in 1989 by two teen advice shows called ''What's Up, Dr. Ruth?'' and a call-in show, ''You're on the Air with Dr. Ruth'' in 1990.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Brooks|first1=Tim|last2=Marsh|first2=Earle F.|title=The Complete Directory to Prime Time Network and Cable TV Shows, 1946-Present|date=2007|publisher=Ballantine Books|location=New York City|isbn=978-0-345-49773-4|url=https://books.google.com/?id=w8KztFy6QYwC&pg=PA373&dq=dr.+ruth+lifetime+tv+show#v=onepage&q=dr.%20ruth%20lifetime%20tv%20show&f=false|accessdate=March 25, 2017}}</ref> In 1993 Westheimer and Israeli TV host, Arad Nir, hosted a talk show in Hebrew titled ''Min Tochnit'', on the newly opened Israeli Channel 2. The show was similar to her US ''Sexually Speaking'' show. The name of the show, ''Min Tochnit'', is a play on words: literally \"Kind of a program\", but \"Min\" (\u05de\u05d9\u05df) in Hebrew also means \"[[sex]]\" and \"[[gender]]\".<ref name=\"imdb\">{{cite web|title=Min Tochnit|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0332951/|website=IMDB|accessdate=March 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 1980s \"Dr. Ruth\" became a household name; she made guest appearances on several [[network television]] shows, including ''[[The Tonight Show Starring Johnny Carson]]'' and ''[[Late Night with David Letterman]]''.<ref name=\"Wolf\">{{cite book|last1=Wolf|first1=Michelle Andrea|last2=Kielwasser, Aldred P.|title=Gay People, Sex, and the Media|date=1991|publisher=The Haworth Press|location=New York City; London|isbn=0-86656-936-7|page=142|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Y_Hd0F2J7LEC&pg=PA142&lpg=PA142&dq=david+letterman+westheimer#v=onepage&q=david%20letterman%20westheimer&f=false}}</ref> She also made frequent appearances on the syndicated revival of ''[[Hollywood Squares]]'' that ran from 1986 to 1989. In the 1990s Westheimer appeared as herself in [[Quantum Leap (season 5)|episode 89]] of ''[[Quantum Leap (TV series)|Quantum Leap]]'', the episode title being \"Dr. Ruth\". She appeared on [[Tom Chapin]]'s album ''This Pretty Planet'', in the song \"Two Kinds of Seagulls\", in which she and Chapin sing of various animals that reproduce sexually. \"It takes two to tingle\" says the song. Dr. Ruth also appeared in several commercial advertisements, including a 1994 [[Honda Prelude]] ad and an ad for [[Clairol]] [[Herbal Essences]] [[shampoo]] and body wash.<ref name=\"prelude\">{{cite journal|title=Dr. Ruth pilots Prelude ad.|journal=Advertising Age|date=October 1994|volume=65|issue=42|page=45|url=http://connection.ebscohost.com/c/articles/9410190935/dr-ruth-pilots-prelude-ad|accessdate=March 25, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"clairol\">{{cite web|title=Clairol Herbal Essences \u2013 Dr. Ruth (1990)|url=http://www.retrojunk.com/commercial/show/1653/clairol-herbal-essences-dr-ruth|website=www.retrojunk.com|accessdate=March 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\nBetween 2001 and 2007, Westheimer made regular appearances on the [[PBS]] children's television series ''[[Between the Lions]]'' as \"Dr. Ruth Wordheimer\" in a spoof of her therapist role in which she helps anxious readers and spellers overcome their fear of long words. In January 2009, the 55th anniversary issue of ''[[Playboy]]'' magazine included Westheimer as #13 in a list of the 55 most important people in sex from the past 55 years.<ref name=\"Geller\">{{cite news|last1=Geller|first1=Adam|title=At 84, legendary sex therapist Dr. Ruth still has lots to talk about.|url=http://www.masslive.com/living/index.ssf/2012/07/post_134.html|accessdate=March 25, 2017|publisher=Masslive|date=July 25, 2012}}</ref> In October 2013 the play ''Becoming Dr. Ruth'' opened Off Broadway. Actress [[Debra Jo Rupp]] played the role of Dr. Ruth. The play showcased the sex therapist's life from fleeing the Nazis in the Kindertransport and joining the [[Haganah]] in Jerusalem as a scout and sniper, to her struggles to succeed as a single mother coming to America.<ref name=\"Rooney\">{{cite news|last1=Rooney|first1=David|title=The Sex Therapist's Story, From Calamity to Clich\u00e9.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/10/30/theater/reviews/becoming-dr-ruth-with-debra-jo-rupp-at-westside-theater.html|accessdate=March 25, 2017|newspaper=New York Times|date=October 29, 2013}}</ref> [[Eileen DeSandre]] played Dr. Ruth in the Virginia Repertory Theatre production of ''Becoming Dr. Ruth''.<ref name=\"Wren\">{{cite news|last1=Wren|first1=Celia|title=Virginia Rep production brings Dr. Ruth, and her story, to Richmond.|url=http://www.richmond.com/entertainment/theater/virginia-rep-production-brings-dr-ruth-and-her-story-to/article_403aceea-1446-54f6-8f37-5ce2a6bbafb7.html|accessdate=March 25, 2017|publisher=Richmond Times-Dispatch|date=September 13, 2014}}</ref>\n\nWestheimer has delivered [[commencement speech]]es at the [[Hebrew Union College]] [[seminary]], [[Lehman College]] of the [[City University of New York]] and, in 2004, at [[Trinity College (Connecticut)|Trinity College]], where she has been awarded [[honorary degree]]s.<ref name=\"Gordon\">{{cite news|last1=Gordon|first1=Jane|title=WORTH NOTING; Calling Dr. Ruth (To Speak at Trinity).|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/05/09/nyregion/worth-noting-calling-dr-ruth-to-speak-at-trinity.html?_r=0|accessdate=March 25, 2017|newspaper=New York Times|date=May 9, 2004}}</ref><ref name=\"dr_ruth_dot_com\" /> She also taught courses and seminars at [[Princeton University|Princeton]] and [[Yale University|Yale]],<ref name=\"Gordon\" /> and was the guest speaker at the [[Bronx High School of Science]] in New York in commemoration of [[Yom HaShoah]] 2008. Westheimer spoke about her life story and the audience of 500 sang \"[[Happy Birthday to You|Happy Birthday]]\" in honor of her 80th birthday. At the ceremony she received an honorary Bronx High School of Science diploma. In 2002, she received the [[Leo Baeck Institute|Leo Baeck Medal]] for her humanitarian work promoting tolerance and [[social justice]].<ref name=\"dr_ruth_dot_com\" />\n\nIn the 1980s and 1990s, Westheimer was a frequent guest on late-night talk shows like ''[[The Tonight Show]]'' and ''[[Late Night with Conan O'Brien]]''. She also appeared on talk shows on German television. In 2019, she was a guest on ''[[The View (talk show)|The View]]'', ''[[The Today Show]]'' and ''[[Late Night with Seth Meyers]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ruth Westheimer|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0922756/?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm#self|website=IMDb|accessdate=May 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\nWestheimer is an accomplished [[ethnographer]]. Her studies in this field include the Ethiopian Jews, [[Papua New Guinea]]'s [[Trobriand Islands|Trobriand Islanders]], and the [[Druze]], a sect originating from [[Shia Islam]] now residing in Israel, Syria and Lebanon. The latter were the subject of her 2007 [[PBS]] documentary ''The Olive and the Tree: The Secret Strength of the Druze'' and a book of the same title.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Treiman|first1=Daniel|title=Dr. Ruth's Other Interest: Ethnography|url=https://forward.com/culture/10768/dr-ruth-s-other-interest-ethnography/|accessdate=May 14, 2019|publisher=[[The Forward]]|date=May 25, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Westheimer|first1=Ruth|last2=Sedan|first2=Gil|title=The Olive and the Tree: The Secret Strength of the Druze|date=2007|publisher=Lantern Books|location=New York City|isbn=978-1-59056-102-7|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/The_Olive_and_the_Tree.html?id=kY0oedX32BwC|accessdate=May 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\nWestheimer is a trustee of the [[Museum of Jewish Heritage]] in New York City.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bruce Ratner And Dr. Ruth Westheimer Preview \"Auschwitz. Not Long Ago. Not Far Away.\"|url=https://mjhnyc.org/bruce-ratner-and-dr-ruth-westheimer-preview-auschwitz-not-long-ago-not-far-away/|accessdate=May 14, 2019|work=[[Museum of Jewish Heritage]]|date=April 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\nA documentary about her life, ''[[Ask Dr. Ruth]]'', premiered in U.S. theaters on May 3, 2019 and will be released on [[Hulu]] on June 1, 2019.{{Update inline|date=January 2020|reason=}} Having previously avoided discussing her early years and how the Holocaust affected her family and herself, Westheimer believes that current events make it necessary for her to \"stand up and be counted.\" She stated that seeing child refugees being separated from their parents upsets her, because her own story is reflected in what they are going through.<ref>{{cite news|title=In 'Ask Dr. Ruth,' The Famous Sex Therapist Looks Inward At Last|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/05/04/720119559/in-ask-dr-ruth-the-famous-sex-therapist-looks-inward-at-last?t=1557828438553|accessdate=May 14, 2019|publisher=[[NPR]]|date=May 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\nWestheimer continues to be an active figure. In addition to the documentary released about her this year, she has recently published her 45th book. On her 91st birthday (June 4), Westheimer visited the Ellen DeGeneres show,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8IiwJf6fR98|title=Dr. Ruth Teaches Ellen the Best Way to Say 'Sex'|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and visited Ellen's show again in November 2019, taking questions from the audience.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8kI8tnefeds|title=Dr. Ruth Answers the Audience's Sex Questions|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In 2019 alone, Westheimer has appeared on ''Late Night with Seth Meyers'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SS1O2D_y3Ko|title=Dr. Ruth Westheimer Gave Advice About a Sex Position on Twitter|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> ''The View'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=22iugomBdrg|title=Dr. Ruth on why she's concerned about millennials\u2019 \u2018loneliness\u2019 and answers sex questions|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and ''Strahan, Sara and Keke''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BhJEPUXZqJg|title=Dr. Ruth Answers Your Sex Questions|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\n[[File:Dr. Ruth Westheimer 2009.jpg|thumb|Dr. Ruth Westheimer in 2009.]]\nWestheimer has been married three times.<ref name=\"NatGeo\" /> She said that each of her marriages played an important role in her relationship advice, but after two divorces, it was her third marriage, to Manfred 'Fred' Westheimer, that was the \"real marriage\".<ref name=\"2013_usatoday\" /> She met Fred on a skiing trip in the Catskills. Fred, too, had escaped Nazi Germany.<ref>{{cite news| title =Love and Loss| newspaper =[[People (magazine)|People]]| date =October 20, 1997| url=https://people.com/archive/love-and-loss-vol-48-no-16/| accessdate=May 14, 2019}}</ref> Their marriage lasted until his death in 1997. She has two children, Miriam and [[Joel Westheimer|Joel]], and four grandchildren.<ref name=\"2013_usatoday\" /><ref name=\"dr_ruth_dot_com\" /> In December 2014, Westheimer was a guest at an Orthodox Jewish wedding in the [[The Bronx|Bronx]]. The groom, Rabbi Benjamin Goldschmidt, is the great-grandson of the woman who had helped rescue Westheimer from Nazi Germany.<ref name=Brawarsky>{{cite news|last1=Brawarsky|first1=Sandee|title=Vows Taking Their Sweet Time|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/21/fashion/weddings/taking-their-time.html|accessdate=December 27, 2014|newspaper=The New York Times|date=December 21, 2014}}</ref> She still lives in the \"cluttered three-bedroom apartment in Washington Heights where she raised her two children and became famous, in that order,\"<ref name=\"residence\">{{cite news| first =Joanne| last =Kaufman| title =Dr. Ruth Westheimer: Her Bedrooms Are Off Limits| quote =| newspaper =[[The New York Times]]| date =November 29, 2013| url =https://www.nytimes.com/2013/12/01/realestate/dr-ruth-westheimer-her-bedrooms-are-off-limits.html| accessdate =July 30, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Salisbury\">{{cite news| first =Vanita| last =Salisbury| title =Dr. Ruth Has Seen the Play About Her Life More Than Fifteen Times| quote =| newspaper =[[New York (magazine)|New York]]| date = November 27, 2013| url =http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2013/11/dr-ruth-21-questions.html| accessdate = July 30, 2015}}</ref> to be near the two [[synagogue]]s of which she is a member, the [[Jewish Community Center|YMHA]] of which she was president for three years, and a \"still sizable community of German Jewish World War II refugees.\"<ref name=\"Morris\" /> She speaks English, German, French, and [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]].\n\n== Bibliography ==\n\n* {{cite book|last1=Westheimer|first1=Ruth K.|title=Dr.Ruth's Guide to Good Sex.|year=1983|publisher=Warner Books|location=New York City|isbn=978-0-446-51260-2|url=https://archive.org/details/drruthsguidetogo00west}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Westheimer|first1=Ruth K.|last2=Kravetz, Nathan|title=First Love: A Young People's Guide to Sexual Information|year=1985|publisher=Warner Books|location=New York City|isbn=978-0-446-34092-2}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Westheimer|first1=Ruth K.|title=Dr. Ruth's Guide for Married Lovers.|url=https://archive.org/details/drruthsguideform00west|url-access=registration|year=1986|publisher=Warner Books|location=New York City|isbn=978-0-446-51282-4}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Westheimer|first1=Ruth K.|title=Dr. Ruth's Guide to Good Sex.|year=1987|publisher=W.H. Allen / Virgin Books|location=London, England|isbn=978-0-491-03377-0}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Westheimer|first1=Ruth K.|title=All in a Lifetime: An Autobiography.|year=1988|publisher=Grand Central Publishing|location=New York City|isbn=978-0-446-34774-7}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Westheimer|first1=Ruth K.|last2=Lieberman, Louis|title=Sex and Morality: Who Is Teaching Our Sex Standards.|year=1988|publisher=Harcourt|location=San Diego, California|isbn=978-0-15-181390-2|url=https://archive.org/details/sexmoralitywhois00west}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Westheimer|first1=Ruth K.|last2=Lieberman, Louis|title=Dr. Ruth's Guide to Erotic and Sensuous Pleasures.|url=https://archive.org/details/drruthsguidetoer00west|url-access=registration|year=1992|publisher=Spi Books Trade|isbn=978-1-56171-035-5}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Westheimer|first1=Ruth K.|title=Dr Ruth\"s Guide to Safer Sex.|year=1992|publisher=Boxtree|location=London|isbn=978-1-85283-430-2}}